{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-js","path":"/blog/wwfinsider-in-1-minute-saving-the-great-whales/","result":{"data":{"wpgraphql":{"post":{"title":"WWF Insider: Saving the Great Whales","content":"\n<p style=\"font-size:24px\"><strong>A minute a day to save wildlife</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<p><em>The next 1 minute will tell you if the world is doing enough for our wildlife.</em></p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW264767.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2474\" srcset=\"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW264767.jpg 1000w, https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW264767-300x171.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px\" /><figcaption><strong>An Antarctic minke whale in the Antarctic Peninsula.</strong><br/><em>© WWF-Australia / Chris Johnson</em></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>You probably don’t know this but every day this week, the fates of <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><a href=\"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wildlife/2016/10/why-these-5-wildlife-species-matter-to-singapore/\">endangered wildlife</a></span> will be decided.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Here, our bite-sized pictorial updates about wildlife (ICYMI: check out our previous <em>#WWFInsider in 1 Minute</em> <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><a href=\"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wildlife/2018/10/wwfinsider-in-1-minute-are-we-doing-enough-to-protect-wildlife/\">here</a></span>) as we take you through the 70th CITES Standing Committee (1-5 Oct) which also leads up to London Illegal Wildlife Trade Conference (11-12 Oct).</p>\n\n\n\n<p><a href=\"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wildlife/2016/09/singapore-and-cites-cop17/\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">CITES</span></a>, or the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora, is supported by the United Nations.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW22103.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2457\" srcset=\"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW22103.jpg 1000w, https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW22103-300x200.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px\" /><figcaption><strong>A sei whale calf diving underwater in the North Pacific. Countries like Japan, Norway and Iceland kill around 1,500 whales every year.</strong><br/><em>© naturepl.com / Doug Perrine / WWF</em><br/></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p style=\"font-size:20px\"><strong>Commercial whaling: Biggest threat to the endangered sei whale </strong><br/></p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW2514.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2462\" srcset=\"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW2514.jpg 1000w, https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW2514-300x200.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px\" /><figcaption><strong>A whale meat stand at the touristy Tsukiji Fish Market in Tokyo, Japan. 50 sei whales are killed every year by Japanese whalers.</strong><br/><em>© Michel Gunther / WWF</em><br/></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW264754.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2507\" srcset=\"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW264754.jpg 1000w, https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW264754-300x200.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px\" /><figcaption><strong>WWF-Australia has provided funding for three ‘whale cams’ to help scientists better understand critical feeding areas in the Southern Ocean.</strong><br/><em>© WWF-Australia / Chris Johnson</em></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-embed-youtube wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-youtube wp-has-aspect-ratio wp-embed-aspect-16-9\"><div class=\"wp-block-embed__wrapper\">\n<iframe title=\"First Camera To Ever Be Attached to a Minke Whale | WWF-Australia\" width=\"580\" height=\"326\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/ctAO_aPek_Q?feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\n</div><figcaption><strong>For the first time ever in world history, scientists in Antarctica have deployed the first camera tag on a minke.</strong></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW264780.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2469\" srcset=\"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW264780.jpg 1000w, https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW264780-300x200.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px\" /><figcaption><strong>All great whales, including the humpback whale (above), receive the highest levels of protection from international trade through a listing on CITES Appendix I. It is strictly illegal to take them from international waters for commercial trade.</strong><br/><em>© WWF-Australia / Chris Johnson</em></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p style=\"font-size:20px\"><strong>How does an international body for wildlife trade like CITES help in whale protection?</strong><br/></p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW182652.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2480\" srcset=\"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW182652.jpg 1000w, https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW182652-300x190.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px\" /><figcaption><strong>In the past, an international law permits country governments to issue “research permits” for whales because killing whales was the only way to obtain research knowledge.</strong><br/><em>© Jürgen Freund / WWF</em><br/></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW2526.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2487\" srcset=\"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW2526.jpg 1000w, https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW2526-300x200.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px\" /><figcaption><strong>Today, Japan has been flagged by CITES for violating international laws on sei whales.</strong><br/><em>© John Dudeny / WWF-Australia</em></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW22034.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2479\" srcset=\"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW22034.jpg 1000w, https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW22034-300x200.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px\" /><figcaption><strong>Disturbing outcome: Even though this issue has been flagged for Parties for 15 years, the 70th CITES Standing Committee deferred any action until May 2019.</strong><br/><em>© naturepl.com / Doug Perrine / WWF</em></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p style=\"font-size:20px\"><strong>What&#8217;s next? </strong></p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW2508.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2472\" srcset=\"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW2508.jpg 1000w, https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW2508-300x200.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px\" /><figcaption><strong>Leigh Henry, Wildlife Policy Director, WWF-US said, “Japan has been conducting so-called “scientific” whaling for years, landing thousands of tons of whale meat and actively marketing the products.&#8221;</strong><br/><em>© Michel Gunther / WWF</em><br/></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW180031.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2490\" srcset=\"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW180031.jpg 1000w, https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Small_WW180031-300x200.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px\" /><figcaption><strong>Japan now has to stop issuing permits, whaling ships from sailing and most importantly, submit a compliance plan to CITES by February 2019.</strong><br/><em>© James Frankham / WWF</em></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>Want to know more? Find out how WWF supports the International Whaling Commission to reduce threats to whale <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><a href=\"http://wwf.panda.org/knowledge_hub/endangered_species/cetaceans/cetaceans/iwc/\">here</a></span>. </strong></p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong></strong><br/><strong><em>Stay tuned to this space for more 1-min updates on global developments in wildlife protection.</em></strong></p>\n","uri":"wwfinsider-in-1-minute-saving-the-great-whales/","author":{"name":"Janissa Ng","slug":"janissa-ng","avatar":{"url":"https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/878af2e67bd7d4b058ec3d614d76ab36?s=96&d=mm&r=g"}},"tags":{"nodes":[{"name":"CITES standing committee","link":"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/tag/cites-standing-committee/"},{"name":"commercial whaling","link":"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/tag/commercial-whaling/"},{"name":"Endangered Species","link":"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/tag/endangered-species/"},{"name":"great whales","link":"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/tag/great-whales/"},{"name":"japanese whaling","link":"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/tag/japanese-whaling/"},{"name":"sei whales","link":"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/tag/sei-whales/"}]},"categories":{"nodes":[{"name":"Climate Change","link":"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/category/climate-change/"}]}}}},"pageContext":{"isCreatedByStatefulCreatePages":false,"id":"cG9zdDoyNDU2","uri":"wwfinsider-in-1-minute-saving-the-great-whales/","title":"WWF Insider: Saving the Great Whales","databaseId":2456,"slug":"wwfinsider-in-1-minute-saving-the-great-whales","excerpt":"<p>A minute a day to save wildlife The next 1 minute will tell you if the world is doing enough for our wildlife. You probably don’t know this but every day this week, the fates of endangered wildlife will be decided. Here, our bite-sized pictorial updates about wildlife (ICYMI: check out our previous #WWFInsider in 1 Minute here) [&hellip;]</p>\n","date":"2018-10-04T18:26:48"}}}